        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-03-30 10:32:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/b7a7da0c-b7ef-11e3-ac5f-52540035b04c).  Ran 19 tests.  2 tests failed: sanity-hsm, sanity-lfsck.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0b0ad6cef6205b06222656bbc1e5aa04c16054f5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-04-01 06:50:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBut if blocksize isn't explicitly specified, ZFS sets it to 512 bytes. I wonder whether that's a good choice, e.g. for drives with native 4K sectors.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9b961e13c37dcfe812f598c56c63e5ef29f705b8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-01 06:52:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI'd think this is responsibility of ZFS to do allocation properly.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ea367f0f8df6533c163e5973c737de91baf55764",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-04-01 23:10:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI tend to think this is similar to setting blocksize when formatting a local FS, e.g. mke2fs -b block-size. The admin knows better how the FS is going to be used and can hopefully make a better choice of block-size. Here zfs allows block-size to be set per object, and we know better how an object is going to be used, so it seems to me that the block-size should be set by the osd-zfs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9b883fd7d5a56e71d60452614e2e1d7a128e0ae1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-02 02:13:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIf ZFS is setting the blocksize to 512 it is a bug. It should be set using the ashift value, which will already be 4096 for modern AF drives. \n\nThat said, I don't mind being able to specify the blocksize from within Lustre. In some cases this will be useful, such as when the client is already doing large writes.\n\nThe ZFS code would ideally increase the blocksize dynamically depending on the file size. I think the ZFS VFS code does this, but there is some reason why this does not work with Lustre.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c1ce8dcd7705fa9bf4d139193f52bcafb132655c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-02 05:07:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nwell, basically this is what I meant - to allow ZFS to choose and change blocksize.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "92a434de673851fce5c1d01f8ad3d1ac7ce9401d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-04-03 17:40:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe ZFS VFS code does change blocksize as file grows, e.g. in zfs_write()->zfs_grow_blocksize(). But my understanding is that the osd-zfs just opens the objset and manipulate it directly by the DMU API, shortcutting ZFS VFS layers - i.e. it never enters the ZFS VFS/Posix code. If this is the case then the zfs_grow_blocksize() stuff will not work for us.\n\nOf course I could have missed something, and please point it out to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c79e11a6cfc7c6542c77e0d62affc1b88773acc3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-03 17:43:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\ncorrect, we don't use ZPL for number of reasons (e.g. we want own transactions).  in some cases this mean we have to duplicate ZPL functionality - this is exactly the case with growing blocksize.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "fce3446bc540251b8c5fa2b2af9c04982e3efca1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-04-06 20:02:53.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nOpened LU-4865 to track dynamic blocksize growth.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    }
  ],
